As for searching an item in an ArrayList, all you needed to do was google &#39;Search ArrayList Java&#39; and you would have found the help you needed. You really rarely need to ask a new question on StackOverFlow.

To check if an item exists in an ArrayList, there are several ways:
 Lets suppose:
    
    ArrayList&lt;String&gt; aList= new ArrayList&lt;&gt;(Arrays.asList(&quot;A&quot;, &quot;B&quot;, &quot;C&quot;));

 Then you can check if an element exists using following methods:

 **1 - `Contains()`**

     if(aList.contains(&quot;A&quot;)){
       // &quot;A&quot; exists in the list
     }else{
      //&quot;A&quot; doesn&#39;t exist in the list
     }
 **2 - `IndexOf()`**

     //This will return the index of the element you&#39;re looking for
     if(aList.indexOf(&quot;A&quot;) &gt; -1){
       //&quot;A&quot; exists 
     }else{//&quot;A&quot; doesn&#39;t exist}

 **3 - Basic Looping**

 You can also use a for each loop to see if an array contains something

    for(item in aList){
     if(item == &quot;A&quot;){
       return true;
     }
    }
    return false;

 **4  - `Iterator()`**

You can also use an `Iterator` to traverse a collection

    Iterator&lt;String&gt; iterator = aList.iterator();
        while (iterator.hasNext()) {
            String value = iterator.next();
            if (value == &quot;A&quot;) {
                return true;
            }
        }
        return false;

 **5  - `Stream API`**
    Stream API allows you to use advanced filters.

    String item = aList.stream().filter(item -&gt; item == &quot;A&quot;).findAny().orElse(null)


Reference : [Finding a list element in Java][1]


  [1]: https://www.baeldung.com/find-list-element-java

